GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 676
Short Title: The North Carolina Survivors' Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Grafstein (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW FOR MITIGATED SENTENCING FOR SURVIVORS OF DOMESTIC
3 VIOLENCE AND OTHER FORMS OF ABUSE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as the North Carolina
6 Survivors' Act.
7 SECTION 2. Article 81B of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Part
8 to read:
9 "Part 4. Survivor Sentencing.
10 "§ 15A-1340.26. Survivor sentencing; generally.
11 (a) Applicability. – Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, this Part shall
12 apply to criminal sentencing under this Chapter, G.S. 20-138.1, and any other provision of law
13 purporting to sentence a criminal defendant.
14 (b) Definitions. – Unless the context requires otherwise, the following definitions apply
15 in this Part:
16 (1) Domestic violence. – An act of physical harm or the threat of imminent
17 physical harm which is committed by an adult, emancipated minor, or minor
18 child 13 years of age or older against an adult, emancipated minor, or minor
19 child who is currently or was previously an intimate partner, a family member,
20 or a household member.
21 (2) Physical abuse. – Any real or threatened physical injury or damage to the body
22 that is not accidental.
23 (3) Post-traumatic stress disorder. – The same as the term is defined in the
24 Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition (DSM-5,
25 2013), and occurred as a result of the victimization of a survivor related to the
26 violence or abuse.
27 (4) Psychological abuse. – A pattern of real or threatened mental intimidation,
28 threats, coercive control, economic or financial control, and humiliation that
29 provokes fear of harm.
30 (5) Sentencing hearing. – A post-conviction hearing in which the defendant is
31 brought before the court for imposition of a sentence.
32 "§ 15A-1340.27. Survivor sentencing; original sentencing hearing.
33 (a) During a hearing to sentence a person or for a person to accept a plea of guilty, when
34 that person is a survivor of domestic violence and has been charged with a crime, the court shall
35 consider as a mitigating factor that the person has been abused physically, sexually, or
36 psychologically by the person's sexual partner, family member, or member of the household, the
*S676-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 trafficker of the person, or other individual who used the person for financial gain. The defendant
2 shall provide to the court evidence including but not limited to each of the following:
3 (1) Documentary evidence corroborating that the defendant was, at the time of
4 the offense, a victim of domestic violence.
5 (2) At least one piece of documentary evidence that is a court record, presentence
6 report, social services record, hospital record, sworn statement from a witness
7 to the domestic violence or abuse who is not the defendant, law enforcement
8 record, domestic incident report, or protective order.
9 (3) Local confinement facility records, records of the Department of Adult
10 Correction, documentation prepared at or near the time of the commission or
11 prosecution of the offense tending to support the claims of the defendant, or
12 verification of consultation with a licensed medical care provide or mental
13 health care provider, employee of a court acting within the scope of the
14 employee's employment, member of the clergy, attorney, social worker, rape
15 crisis counselor, or other advocate acting on behalf of an agency that assists
16 victims of domestic violence or abuse. Expert testimony from a psychiatrist,
17 psychologist or mental health professional showing that the defendant has
18 been diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder as a result of the violence
19 or abuse at issue may also be submitted to the court as evidence.
20 (b) If the court finds by clear and convincing evidence that at the time of the offense the
21 defendant was a survivor of domestic violence or subjected to physical, sexual, or psychological
22 abuse inflicted by a sexual partner, family member, or member of the household, the trafficker
23 of the defendant, or any person who used the defendant for financial gain, and that the violence
24 or abuse was related to and was a substantial contributing factor in causing the defendant to
25 commit the offense or to the defendant's criminal behavior, the court shall depart from the
26 applicable sentence to the ranges provided as follows:
27 (1) Sentences of life without the possibility of parole shall be reduced to 30 years
28 or less.
29 (2) Sentences of life with the possibility of parole shall be reduced to 25 years or
30 less.
31 (3) Sentences of 30 years or more shall be reduced to 20 years or less.
32 (4) Sentences of 20 years or more shall be reduced to 15 years or less.
33 (5) Sentences of 15 years or more shall be reduced to 7.5 years or less.
34 (6) Sentences of 8 years or more shall be reduced to 5 years or less.
35 (c) The provisions of this section shall not apply to a person convicted of any of the
36 following:
37 (1) An offense that would require the person to register as a sex offender.
38 (2) An attempt or conspiracy to commit an offense that would require the person
39 to register as a sex offender.
40 (3) An offense under any of the following:
41 a. G.S. 14-32.3.
42 b. G.S. 14-112.2.
43 c. Article 7B of Chapter 14, when committed against a victim that has a
44 mental disability or who is mentally incapacitated or physically
45 helpless, and the person committing the offense knows or should
46 reasonably know that the victim has a mental disability or is mentally
47 incapacitated or physically helpless.
48 (4) An offense under any of the following:
49 a. G.S. 14-318.2.
50 b. G.S. 14-318.4.
51 c. Article 7B of Chapter 14, when committed against a child.
