1 (5) An offense for which the person has received a sentence of death.
2 "§ 15A-1340.28. Survivor sentencing; application for person previously sentenced.
3 (a) Where a court has imposed a criminal judgment and sentence upon a defendant other
4 than for an offense described in G.S. 15A-1340.27(c) and the defendant is serving the sentence
5 in the custody of the Department of Adult Correction, the court shall impose a new, lesser
6 sentence following a hearing if the court determines each of the following:
7 (1) At the time of the offense for which the sentence is being served, the defendant
8 was a victim of domestic violence or subjsected to physical, sexual, or
9 psychological abuse inflicted by a sexual partner, a family member or member
10 of the household, the trafficker of the defendant, or any preson who used the
11 defendant for financial gain.
12 (2) The violence or abuse under subdivision (1) of this subsection was related to
13 and was a substantial contributing factor in causing (i) the defendant to
14 commit the offense for which the defendant is presently in custody or (ii) the
15 defendant's criminal behavior.
16 (b) At the hearing to determine whether a defendant should be resentenced pursuant to
17 this section, the court shall take testimony from witnesses offered by the State and the defendant
18 and shall consider oral and written arguments and any other relevant evidence to assist in making
19 its determination. The court may determine that the violence or abuse found pursuant to
20 subsection (a) of this section was related to and was a substantial contributing factor to the offense
21 regardless of whether the defendant raised an affirmative defense.
22 (c) Any person meeting all of the following circumstances may, on or after the date this
23 section becomes effective, submit to the judge who imposed the original sentence a request to
24 apply for resentencing in accordance with the provisions of this section:
25 (1) Confined in an institution under the custody and control of the Department of
26 Adult Correction.
27 (2) Serving a sentence for an offense committed prior to the effective date of this
28 section.
29 (3) Eligible for an alternative sentence pursuant to the provisions of this section.
30 A person making a request under this subsection shall include in the request documentation
31 and declarations to support the person's claims.
32 (d) If, upon receipt of a request pursuant to subsection (c) of this section, the original
33 sentencing judge is not serving on the court in which the original sentence was imposed at the
34 time of the request to apply for resentencing, the request shall be randomly assigned to a judge
35 of the original sentencing court.
36 (e) If the court finds that the person has met the requirements to apply for resentencing
37 as provided in subsection (c) of this section, the court shall provide notice to the person that the
38 person may submit an application for resentencing. Upon receiving this notification, the person
39 may request the court appoint an attorney to assist the person in the preparation of and
40 proceedings on the application for resentencing.
41 (f) If the court finds that the person has not met the requirements to apply for
42 resentencing as provided for in subsection (c) of this section, the court shall notify the person and
43 deny the person's request without prejudice.
44 "§ 15A-1340.29. Survivor sentencing; resentencing hearing for person previously
45 sentenced.
46 (a) Upon receipt of an application for resentencing as authorized by
47 G.S. 15A-1340.28(e), the clerk of court shall promptly notify the district attorney and provide
48 the district attorney with a copy of the application.
49 (b) If the judge that receives an application pursuant to subsection (a) of this section is
50 not the judge who originally sentenced the applicant, the application may be referred to the
Senate Bill 676-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 original sentencing judge if that judge is serving as a judge of a court of competent jurisdiction
2 and the applicant and the district attorney agree that the application should be referred.
3 (c) An application for resentencing received pursuant to this section shall include
4 evidence including but not limited to each of the following:
5 (1) Corroborating the claim of the applicant that the applicant was a victim of
6 domestic violence or subjected to physical, sexual, or psychological abuse
7 inflicted b a sexual partner, a family member or member of the household, the
8 trafficker of the applicant, or any person who used the applicant for financial
9 gain.
10 (2) A court record, presentence report, social services record, hospital record,
11 sworn statement from a witness to the domestic violence who is not the
12 applicant, law enforcement record, domestic incident report, or protective
13 order.
14 (3) Local confinement facility records, records of the Department of Adult
15 Correction, documentation prepared at or near the time of the commission or
16 prosecution of the offense tending to support the claims of the defendant, or
17 verification of consultation with a licensed medical care provide or mental
18 health care provider, employee of a court acting within the scope of the
19 employee's employment, member of the clergy, attorney, social worker, rape
20 crisis counselor, or other advocate acting on behalf of an agency that assists
21 victims of domestic violence or abuse. Expert testimony from a psychiatrist,
22 psychologist or mental health professional showing that the defendant has
23 been diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder as a result of the violence
24 or abuse at issue may also be submitted to the court as evidence.
25 (d) If the court finds that the applicant has not complied with the provisions of subsection
26 (c) of this section, the court shall deny the application without prejudice.
27 (e) If the court finds that the applicant has complied with the provisions of subsection (c)
28 of this section, the court shall conduct a sentencing hearing to aid in making its determination of
29 whether the applicant should be resentenced in accordance with G.S. 15A-1340.27(b). At the
30 hearing, the court shall determine any controverted issues of fact relevant to the issue of
31 sentencing. The court may consider any facts or circumstances relevant to the imposition of a
32 new sentence submitted by the applicant or the district attorney and may consider the institutional
33 record of confinement of the person, provided, however, the institutional record shall not be
34 solely dispositive as to whether an applicant receives a reduced sentence. The court shall not
35 order a new presentence investigation and report or entertain any matter challenging the
36 underlying basis of the subject conviction. Consideration of the institutional record of
37 confinement of an applicant by the court shall include, but not be limited to, the participation of
38 the applicant in programming for domestic violence, parenting, and substance abuse treatment
39 while incarcerated, and the disciplinary history of the applicant. The inability of the applicant to
40 participate in treatment or other programming while incarcerated despite the willingness of the
41 applicant to do so shall not be considered a negative factor when the court is making its decision.
42 (f) If the court determines after a hearing under subsection (e) of this section that the
43 applicant should not be resentenced in accordance with G.S. 15A-1340.27(b), the court shall
44 inform the applicant of its decision and shall enter an order to that effect. Any order issued by a
45 court pursuant to this subsection shall include written findings of fact and the reasons for the
46 order. If the applicant is denied on the merits of the application, the court shall deny the applicant
47 with prejudice.
48 (g) If the court determines after a hearing under subsection (e) of this section that the
49 applicant should be resentenced in accordance with G.S. 15A-1340.27(b), the court shall notify
50 the applicant that, unless the applicant withdraws the application for resentencing or appeals the
51 order of the court, the court shall enter an order vacating the sentence originally imposed and
Page 4 Senate Bill 676-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall impose a new sentence as set forth in G.S. 15A-1340.27(b). Any order issued by a court
2 pursuant to this subsection shall include written findings of fact and the reasons for the order.
3 Sentences modified pursuant to the provisions of this subsection shall be reduced as set forth in
4 G.S. 15A-1340.27(b). When calculating the new sentence to be served by the applicant, the
5 applicant shall be credited for any time served in a local confinement facility or in the custody of
6 the Department of Adult Correction toward the sentence originally imposed.
7 (h) An appeal to the Court of Appeals may be taken as of right from an order under this
8 section denying resentencing or ordering a new sentence be imposed. Pursuant to an appeal under
9 this subsection, the applicant may request that the Court of Appeals direct the Appellate Defender
10 to assist the applicant in the preparation of the appeal and represent the applicant during the
11 subsequent appellate proceedings."
12 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective December 1, 2025.
